        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We plan to use the correlator in spectral mode which gives formally 202 channels over ~4900kms (and 2.55km/s resolution). We plan to resolve the CO line in 34 channels using a user frequency width of 15km/s and assuming for the width the a priori knowledge of the JCMT CO(3-2) width (516km/s). With this set-up we will trace the molecular line and compare with the observed stellar, ionized and cold-HI line properties.
The other three base-bands are set to the continuum mode (31.250MHz bandwidth) to obtain the continuum information at 101-103-113GHz observed frequency.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>With these observations we plan to discuss the content, distribution, and kinematics of the CO as tracer of the molecular gas, thus we opt for using the ALMA configuration to obtain an angular resolution of 1arcsec (1arcsec=100pc). This is the typical size of giant molecular clouds. With this observational set-up we obtain a mosaic of 7arcmin x 1arcmin (7kpc x 1kpc) with 49 pointings where we sample both the main optical body of NGC5719 and the brightest condensations of 21cm-HI gas. With this set-up we complement the knowledge of the ISM physical conditions obtained from resolved (optical and radio) line images at 1arcsec (100pc, similar ALMA resolution) over 3kpc^2 and over many tens of kpc with beam=15arcsec, respectively. The largest angular scale we want to discuss is set by our 21cm-HI VLA observations to 15arcsec.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We derive an rms noise of 3mJy assuming the line peak flux derived from the JCMT observations (85Jy over 55arcsec) and a line width of 516km/s  rescaled to our 1arcsec spatial beam with a 10sigma detection: (1arcsec/55arcsec)^2*85.112Jy/10. This computation assumes to have similar fluxes in the two transitions of the CO (1-0) and CO(3-2) that cannot be necessarily true all over the regions. Despite the fact that the JCMT integrated flux spectrum of both the transition CO(1-0) and CO(3-2) for the companion NG5713 show similar fluxes and profiles. No observations are available for NGC5719 at CO(1-0) to have stronger constraints. Thus in those channels where the CO(1-0) is expected to have even half a flux of the CO(3-2) transition, the confidence level of the detection will decrease down to 5 (from 10) still sufficient to achieve this project. 
We can carry out our programme with a total integration time of 3.32h for the 49 pointings of the mosaic that covers the central 7arcmin x 1arcmin. This region covers the optical body and the highest condensations of 21cm-HI at the tip of the bridges where the majority of the molecular content is expected. If the molecular gas is not distributed homogeneusly over a disk but concentrated in the nucleus we will collect all the CO flux in less indipendent beams giving an upper limit in the periphery.
We obtain the CO(1-0) line over 34 channels using a 15km/s spectral bandwidth to trace the content, geometry, and kinematics of the molecular component. The additional 3 basebands are set to the continuum correlators resulting in deep observations allowing us to trace the dust content (temperature) and distribution.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
